\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 presents the parametrizations and distributions considered, as well as
 their empirical variance and skewness.
 There is a wide range of variance and skewnesses considered.
 Variance ranges from 1 to nearly 300, while skewness ranges from -0.18 to
 nearly 7.
 These distributions provide a starting point for understanding whether
 Condorcet cycles can arise 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

naturally.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As with the example devised above, the margins in the cycle are fairly small.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 beats 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 51% of the time.
 Since our simulations estimate win probabilities with error,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We use 100,000 simulations.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the determination of what constitutes a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

significant
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 win probability is essential.
 To calibrate this choice of the margin required for a preference to be
 considered significant, we rely on the theory in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Since we know for symmetric distributions, only expected values, all uniform,
 normal, and discrete uniform specifications should perform identically.
 Of the 21 pairs of these 7 distributions (3 uniform, 1 normal, 3 discrete
 uniform), the maximum difference between in winning probabilities is 0.64%.
 Thus, any margin that is greater than 0.64 should be significant at the
 5% level.
 We thus set the critical margin to 0.64.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using 0.64 as the critical margin, we observe a cycle between distributions
 1, 18, and 6.
 Distribution 1 beats 18 by a margin of 0.7%, 18 beats 6 by 2.04%, and 6 beats
 1 by 1%.
 Similar to the example above, the margins are fairly small.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These margins are close to the critical margin of 0.64, but our simulations
 do not allow for greater power in this test.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thus, out of the 231 pairs of distributions considered, there is a cycle
 between the 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left[0,20\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Weibull\left[10,10.51\right]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $HypGeom\left[20,40,30\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These cycles are interesting phenomena.
 Not only do they violate a key axiom in standard preferences, but also
 form intersting game-theoretic applications.
 The presence of cycles essentially affects whether the first mover has
 an advantage.
 If cycles did not exist, players in a sequential game would simply choose
 the item that performed the best against other items.
 Since there are no cycles, there is a globally-preferred option, and player
 2 would only be able to choose the next-best option.
 However, if there were cycles in all items, the first-mover would be guaranteed
 to lose on average.
 For any item player 1 chose, player 2 would be able to choose another item
 that performed relatively better.
 In the case in which there are cycles with some items, the first mover
 would never choose one of those items, for the same reason.
 This essentially reduces the option set available to the first mover.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Utility Estimation and Minimax
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an extension to our previous simulations, we also consider simulated
 games where players form knapsacks simultaneously, and may unknowingly
 choose the same set of items.
 To analyze the effects of item type (that is, the distributions that items
 draw from), number of players, and number of items, we estimate utility
 for a player in every possible matchup of knapsacks, and then use minimax
 to search for the optimal strategy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Utility Estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate the utility of a given knapsack in a matchup against an any
 number of other knapsacks we take 10,000 draws from each knapsack's distributio
n (in the case where knapsacks are composed of more than one item, each
 knapsack draw is the sum of all item draws), where each draw represents
 a round of play.
 We then find the utility for each round, and take the average.
 Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{w}$
\end_inset

players split win, they each receive utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{n-n_{w}}}{n_{w}}$
\end_inset

.
 The maximum achievable utility for a player in a given match is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,\frac{{1}}{n-1},\frac{{2}}{n-2},\ldots,(n-1)\}$
\end_inset

, where in the first case all players tied, in the second case 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 players tie and one player loses, and in the last case one player wins
 all.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Utility Estimation Example
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Tabular
