\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This approach to utility estimation is intuitive, but requires many draws
 from each distribution for an accurate estimation.
 Furthermore, because there are 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{n}$
\end_inset

(recall: 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 knapsacks, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 players) possible matches, simulating games with many players and many
 items the computational costs are exponential.
 Unfortunately, this has limited the number of simulations we have been
 able to conduct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Minimax
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once utility has been estimated for a given number of players and items,
 we use the minimax approach to solve for an optimal strategy for a given
 player.
 In cases where minimax returns a mixed strategy, we can treat it as a new
 mixture distribution.
 Our implementation of minimax uses the linear programming approach presented
 in lecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Symmetric Distributions and Equal Means
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consistent with our two player variance independence result, when there
 are only two players, minimax advises one choose any given strategy (that
 is, minimax as we have implemented it will put all probability on whichever
 knapsack is first).
 However, when we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $n>2$
\end_inset

, the minimax strategy places probability on a few items with high variance,
 though we have been unable to devise functions to estimate how many items
 minimax randomizes over..
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
