\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While we have had difficulty characterizing minimax strategies, it does
 at least appear that the results are not quite uniform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Future Work and Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Future Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What we have presented here represents only a small part of what might be
 investigated in the adversarial knapsack game.
 In the future, it may be interesting to investigate the following.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Risk Attitudes and Tie Games
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a game with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 players and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 possible knapsacks there are 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{n}$
\end_inset

possible matches.
 Of these, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{m!}}{(m-n)!}$
\end_inset

 matches where each player can play a unique knapsack.
 In the remaining games (
\begin_inset Formula $m^{n}-\frac{{m!}}{(m-n)!}$
\end_inset

) at least two players tie (the most obvious cases being those where all
 players play the same item - there are 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 of these).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{{m}}{n}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, the ratio of matches where all players can play unique knapsacks to number
 of matches where at least some players will tie decreases.
 In the future, it may be interesting to investigate what kinds of players
 prefer games with higher likelihood of a tie (where a low payout is more
 likely) to games with low likelihoods of a tie (but where winning results
 in a large payout).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Number of Items, Item Types, and Players
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While we have been able to generalize some results to scenarios with 
\begin_inset Formula $n`$
\end_inset

players, it would of course be ideal to further investigate the effect of
 increasing the number of items and players on the optimal strategy.
 It may be further interesting to consider knapsacks where some number of
 items need to be of a given type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Conclusion
\end_layout

\end_body
